Understood! Here’s a more detailed implementation of a First Loop setter in JavaScript, including user interaction for starting and stopping the loop:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>First Loop Tempo Setter</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>First Loop Tempo Setter</h1>
    <button id="start">Start Loop</button>
    <button id="stop" disabled>Stop Loop</button>
    <p id="tempo">Tempo will be displayed here.</p>

    <script>
        let startTime, endTime;
        let loopDuration;

        document.getElementById('start').addEventListener('click', () => {
            startTime = Date.now();
            document.getElementById('stop').disabled = false;
            document.getElementById('start').disabled = true;
        });

        document.getElementById('stop').addEventListener('click', () => {
            endTime = Date.now();
            loopDuration = (endTime - startTime) / 1000; // duration in seconds
            const numberOfBars = 4; // adjust according to your loop
            const beatsPerBar = 4; // common time signature (4/4)
            const tempo = Math.round((numberOfBars / loopDuration) * beatsPerBar * 60);

            document.getElementById('tempo').innerText = `The tempo is ${tempo} BPM`;
            document.getElementById('start').disabled = false;
            document.getElementById('stop').disabled = true;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: Simple buttons to start and stop the loop, and a paragraph to display the tempo.
- **JavaScript Logic**:
  - When the "Start Loop" button is clicked, the start time is recorded.
  - The "Stop Loop" button calculates the duration when clicked.
  - It computes the tempo based on the number of bars (4) and beats per bar (4), then displays it.

Feel free to modify the number of bars and time signature to fit your specific needs.

To parse and process the JSON response from the Google Sheets API in Perl, you can use the `JSON` module. Here’s a more detailed breakdown:

### Steps to Parse JSON Response

